{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":1000,"text":"I'm here to enlist you"},{"time":7000,"text":"in helping reshape the story about how humans and other critters get things done."},{"time":15000,"text":"Here is the old story -- we've already heard a little bit about it:"},{"time":20000,"text":"biology is war in which only the fiercest survive;"},{"time":27000,"text":"businesses and nations succeed only by defeating,"},{"time":35000,"text":"destroying and dominating competition;"}]},{"cues":[{"time":41000,"text":"politics is about your side winning at all costs."},{"time":48000,"text":"But I think we can see the very beginnings of a new story beginning to emerge."},{"time":56000,"text":"It's a narrative spread across a number of different disciplines,"},{"time":63000,"text":"in which cooperation, collective action and complex interdependencies"},{"time":71000,"text":"play a more important role."},{"time":74000,"text":"And the central, but not all-important, role of competition and survival of the fittest"},{"time":83000,"text":"shrinks just a little bit to make room."}]},{"cues":[{"time":87000,"text":"I started thinking about the relationship between communication, media"},{"time":94000,"text":"and collective action when I wrote \"Smart Mobs,\""},{"time":99000,"text":"and I found that when I finished the book, I kept thinking about it."},{"time":104000,"text":"In fact, if you look back, human communication media"},{"time":110000,"text":"and the ways in which we organize socially have been co-evolving for quite a long time."},{"time":117000,"text":"Humans have lived for much, much longer"},{"time":121000,"text":"than the approximately 10,000 years of settled agricultural civilization"}]},{"cues":[{"time":128000,"text":"in small family groups. Nomadic hunters bring down rabbits, gathering food."},{"time":136000,"text":"The form of wealth in those days was enough food to stay alive."},{"time":141000,"text":"But at some point, they banded together to hunt bigger game."},{"time":148000,"text":"And we don't know exactly how they did this,"},{"time":151000,"text":"although they must have solved some collective action problems;"},{"time":156000,"text":"it only makes sense that you can't hunt mastodons"},{"time":160000,"text":"while you're fighting with the other groups."}]},{"cues":[{"time":163000,"text":"And again, we have no way of knowing,"},{"time":165000,"text":"but it's clear that a new form of wealth must have emerged."},{"time":170000,"text":"More protein than a hunter's family could eat before it rotted."},{"time":175000,"text":"So that raised a social question"},{"time":177000,"text":"that I believe must have driven new social forms."},{"time":180000,"text":"Did the people who ate that mastodon meat owe something"},{"time":185000,"text":"to the hunters and their families?"},{"time":187000,"text":"And if so, how did they make arrangements?"},{"time":191000,"text":"Again, we can't know, but we can be pretty sure that some form of"},{"time":194000,"text":"symbolic communication must have been involved."}]},{"cues":[{"time":199000,"text":"Of course, with agriculture came the first big civilizations,"},{"time":204000,"text":"the first cities built of mud and brick, the first empires."},{"time":209000,"text":"And it was the administers of these empires"},{"time":213000,"text":"who began hiring people to keep track of the wheat and sheep and wine that was owed"},{"time":219000,"text":"and the taxes that was owed on them"},{"time":221000,"text":"by making marks; marks on clay in that time."}]},{"cues":[{"time":225000,"text":"Not too much longer after that, the alphabet was invented."},{"time":230000,"text":"And this powerful tool was really reserved, for thousands of years,"},{"time":236000,"text":"for the elite administrators (Laughter) who kept track of accounts for the empires."},{"time":246000,"text":"And then another communication technology enabled new media:"},{"time":251000,"text":"the printing press came along, and within decades,"},{"time":256000,"text":"millions of people became literate."},{"time":258000,"text":"And from literate populations,"},{"time":262000,"text":"new forms of collective action emerged in the spheres of knowledge,"},{"time":266000,"text":"religion and politics."},{"time":270000,"text":"We saw scientific revolutions, the Protestant Reformation,"},{"time":275000,"text":"constitutional democracies possible where they had not been possible before."},{"time":281000,"text":"Not created by the printing press,"},{"time":283000,"text":"but enabled by the collective action that emerges from literacy."},{"time":288000,"text":"And again, new forms of wealth emerged."}]},{"cues":[{"time":292000,"text":"Now, commerce is ancient. Markets are as old as the crossroads."},{"time":297000,"text":"But capitalism, as we know it, is only a few hundred years old,"},{"time":301000,"text":"enabled by cooperative arrangements and technologies,"},{"time":306000,"text":"such as the joint-stock ownership company,"},{"time":309000,"text":"shared liability insurance, double-entry bookkeeping."}]},{"cues":[{"time":314000,"text":"Now of course, the enabling technologies are based on the Internet,"},{"time":319000,"text":"and in the many-to-many era, every desktop is now a printing press,"},{"time":326000,"text":"a broadcasting station, a community or a marketplace."},{"time":332000,"text":"Evolution is speeding up."},{"time":335000,"text":"More recently, that power is untethering and leaping off the desktops,"},{"time":341000,"text":"and very, very quickly, we're going to see a significant proportion, if not the majority of"},{"time":347000,"text":"the human race, walking around holding, carrying or wearing supercomputers"},{"time":355000,"text":"linked at speeds greater"},{"time":358000,"text":"than what we consider to be broadband today."}]},{"cues":[{"time":362000,"text":"Now, when I started looking into collective action,"},{"time":365000,"text":"the considerable literature on it is based on what sociologists call \"social dilemmas.\""},{"time":371000,"text":"And there are a couple of mythic narratives of social dilemmas."},{"time":374000,"text":"I'm going to talk briefly about two of them:"},{"time":377000,"text":"the prisoner's dilemma and the tragedy of the commons."}]},{"cues":[{"time":380000,"text":"Now, when I talked about this with Kevin Kelly,"},{"time":382000,"text":"he assured me that everybody in this audience pretty much knows the details"},{"time":386000,"text":"of the prisoner's dilemma,"},{"time":388000,"text":"so I'm just going to go over that very, very quickly."},{"time":391000,"text":"If you have more questions about it, ask Kevin Kelly later. (Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":398000,"text":"The prisoner's dilemma is actually a story that's overlaid"},{"time":401000,"text":"on a mathematical matrix that came out of the game theory"},{"time":405000,"text":"in the early years of thinking about nuclear war:"},{"time":409000,"text":"two players who couldn't trust each other."},{"time":411000,"text":"Let me just say that every unsecured transaction"},{"time":414000,"text":"is a good example of a prisoner's dilemma."},{"time":417000,"text":"Person with the goods, person with the money,"},{"time":420000,"text":"because they can't trust each other, are not going to exchange."},{"time":424000,"text":"Neither one wants to be the first one"},{"time":427000,"text":"or they're going to get the sucker's payoff,"},{"time":429000,"text":"but both lose, of course, because they don't get what they want."},{"time":433000,"text":"If they could only agree, if they could only turn a prisoner's dilemma into"},{"time":437000,"text":"a different payoff matrix called an assurance game, they could proceed."}]},{"cues":[{"time":443000,"text":"Twenty years ago, Robert Axelrod used the prisoner's dilemma"},{"time":447000,"text":"as a probe of the biological question:"},{"time":452000,"text":"if we are here because our ancestors were such fierce competitors,"},{"time":457000,"text":"how does cooperation exist at all?"},{"time":459000,"text":"He started a computer tournament for"},{"time":461000,"text":"people to submit prisoner's dilemma strategies and discovered,"},{"time":466000,"text":"much to his surprise, that a very, very simple strategy won --"},{"time":470000,"text":"it won the first tournament, and even after everyone knew it won,"},{"time":474000,"text":"it won the second tournament -- that's known as tit for tat."}]},{"cues":[{"time":481000,"text":"Another economic game that may not be as well known as the prisoner's dilemma"},{"time":487000,"text":"is the ultimatum game,"},{"time":489000,"text":"and it's also a very interesting probe of"},{"time":491000,"text":"our assumptions about the way people make economic transactions."},{"time":497000,"text":"Here's how the game is played: there are two players;"},{"time":500000,"text":"they've never played the game before,"},{"time":502000,"text":"they will not play the game again, they don't know each other,"},{"time":505000,"text":"and they are, in fact, in separate rooms."},{"time":508000,"text":"First player is offered a hundred dollars"},{"time":510000,"text":"and is asked to propose a split: 50/50, 90/10,"},{"time":516000,"text":"whatever that player wants to propose. The second player either accepts the split --"},{"time":523000,"text":"both players are paid and the game is over --"},{"time":526000,"text":"or rejects the split -- neither player is paid and the game is over."}]},{"cues":[{"time":532000,"text":"Now, the fundamental basis of neoclassical economics"},{"time":536000,"text":"would tell you it's irrational to reject a dollar"},{"time":540000,"text":"because someone you don't know in another room is going to get 99."},{"time":545000,"text":"Yet in thousands of trials with American and European and Japanese students,"},{"time":551000,"text":"a significant percentage would reject any offer that's not close to 50/50."},{"time":557000,"text":"And although they were screened and didn't know about the game"},{"time":562000,"text":"and had never played the game before,"},{"time":564000,"text":"proposers seemed to innately know this"},{"time":567000,"text":"because the average proposal was surprisingly close to 50/50."}]},{"cues":[{"time":573000,"text":"Now, the interesting part comes in more recently"},{"time":575000,"text":"when anthropologists began taking this game to other cultures"},{"time":579000,"text":"and discovered, to their surprise,"},{"time":582000,"text":"that slash-and-burn agriculturalists in the Amazon"},{"time":586000,"text":"or nomadic pastoralists in Central Asia or a dozen different cultures --"},{"time":591000,"text":"each had radically different ideas of what is fair."},{"time":596000,"text":"Which suggests that instead of there being an innate sense of fairness,"},{"time":602000,"text":"that somehow the basis of our economic"},{"time":605000,"text":"transactions can be influenced by our social institutions,"},{"time":611000,"text":"whether we know that or not."}]},{"cues":[{"time":613000,"text":"The other major narrative of social dilemmas is the tragedy of the commons."},{"time":618000,"text":"Garrett Hardin used it to talk about overpopulation in the late 1960s."},{"time":624000,"text":"He used the example of a common grazing area in which each person"},{"time":630000,"text":"by simply maximizing their own flock"},{"time":633000,"text":"led to overgrazing and the depletion of the resource."},{"time":636000,"text":"He had the rather gloomy conclusion that"},{"time":638000,"text":"humans will inevitably despoil any common pool resource"},{"time":643000,"text":"in which people cannot be restrained from using it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":649000,"text":"Now, Elinor Ostrom, a political scientist, in"},{"time":652000,"text":"1990 asked the interesting question that any good scientist should ask,"},{"time":657000,"text":"which is: is it really true that humans will always despoil commons?"},{"time":662000,"text":"So she went out and looked at what data she could find."},{"time":666000,"text":"She looked at thousands of cases of humans sharing watersheds,"},{"time":670000,"text":"forestry resources, fisheries, and discovered that yes, in case after case,"},{"time":677000,"text":"humans destroyed the commons that they depended on."},{"time":681000,"text":"But she also found many instances in which people escaped the prisoner's dilemma;"},{"time":688000,"text":"in fact, the tragedy of the commons is a multiplayer prisoner's dilemma."},{"time":694000,"text":"And she said that people are only prisoners if they consider themselves to be."},{"time":699000,"text":"They escape by creating institutions for collective action."},{"time":703000,"text":"And she discovered, I think most interestingly,"},{"time":707000,"text":"that among those institutions that worked,"},{"time":710000,"text":"there were a number of common design"},{"time":712000,"text":"principles, and those principles seem to be"},{"time":715000,"text":"missing from those institutions that don't work."}]},{"cues":[{"time":719000,"text":"I'm moving very quickly over a number of"},{"time":721000,"text":"disciplines. In biology, the notions of symbiosis,"},{"time":724000,"text":"group selection, evolutionary psychology are contested, to be sure."},{"time":730000,"text":"But there is really no longer any major debate over the fact that"},{"time":735000,"text":"cooperative arrangements have moved from a peripheral role to a central role\n"},{"time":741000,"text":"in biology, from the level of the cell to the level of the ecology."},{"time":747000,"text":"And again, our notions of individuals as economic beings"},{"time":752000,"text":"have been overturned."},{"time":754000,"text":"Rational self-interest is not always the dominating factor."},{"time":759000,"text":"In fact, people will act to punish cheaters, even at a cost to themselves."}]},{"cues":[{"time":767000,"text":"And most recently, neurophysiological measures"},{"time":769000,"text":"have shown that people who punish cheaters in economic games"},{"time":775000,"text":"show activity in the reward centers of their brain."},{"time":779000,"text":"Which led one scientist to declare that altruistic punishment"},{"time":786000,"text":"may be the glue that holds societies together."}]},{"cues":[{"time":790000,"text":"Now, I've been talking about how new forms of communication and new media"},{"time":795000,"text":"in the past have helped create new economic forms."},{"time":799000,"text":"Commerce is ancient. Markets are very old. Capitalism is fairly recent;"},{"time":804000,"text":"socialism emerged as a reaction to that."},{"time":808000,"text":"And yet we see very little talk about how the next form may be emerging."},{"time":814000,"text":"Jim Surowiecki briefly mentioned Yochai Benkler's paper about open source,"},{"time":819000,"text":"pointing to a new form of production: peer-to-peer production."},{"time":823000,"text":"I simply want you to keep in mind that if in the past, new forms of cooperation"},{"time":829000,"text":"enabled by new technologies create new forms of wealth,"},{"time":833000,"text":"we may be moving into yet another economic form"},{"time":837000,"text":"that is significantly different from previous ones."}]},{"cues":[{"time":841000,"text":"Very briefly, let's look at some businesses. IBM, as you know, HP, Sun --"},{"time":847000,"text":"some of the most fierce competitors in the IT world are open sourcing"},{"time":853000,"text":"their software, are providing portfolios of patents for the commons."},{"time":860000,"text":"Eli Lilly -- in, again, the fiercely competitive pharmaceutical world --"},{"time":865000,"text":"has created a market for solutions for pharmaceutical problems."},{"time":871000,"text":"Toyota, instead of treating its suppliers as a marketplace,"},{"time":876000,"text":"treats them as a network and trains them to produce better,"},{"time":880000,"text":"even though they are also training them to produce better for their competitors."},{"time":885000,"text":"Now none of these companies are doing this out of altruism;"},{"time":889000,"text":"they're doing it because they're learning that"},{"time":891000,"text":"a certain kind of sharing is in their self-interest."}]},{"cues":[{"time":897000,"text":"Open source production has shown us that world-class software, like Linux and Mozilla,"},{"time":904000,"text":"can be created with neither the bureaucratic structure of the firm"},{"time":910000,"text":"nor the incentives of the marketplace as we've known them."},{"time":916000,"text":"Google enriches itself by enriching thousands of bloggers through AdSense."},{"time":922000,"text":"Amazon has opened its Application Programming Interface"},{"time":926000,"text":"to 60,000 developers, countless Amazon shops."},{"time":931000,"text":"They're enriching others, not out of altruism but as a way of enriching themselves."},{"time":937000,"text":"eBay solved the prisoner's dilemma and created a market"},{"time":942000,"text":"where none would have existed by creating a feedback mechanism"},{"time":946000,"text":"that turns a prisoner's dilemma game into an assurance game."}]},{"cues":[{"time":951000,"text":"Instead of, \"Neither of us can trust each other, so we have to make suboptimal moves,\""},{"time":956000,"text":"it's, \"You prove to me that you are trustworthy and I will cooperate.\""},{"time":962000,"text":"Wikipedia has used thousands of volunteers to create a free encyclopedia"},{"time":968000,"text":"with a million and a half articles in 200 languages in just a couple of years."}]},{"cues":[{"time":975000,"text":"We've seen that ThinkCycle has enabled NGOs in developing countries"},{"time":982000,"text":"to put up problems to be solved by design students around the world,"},{"time":988000,"text":"including something that's being used for tsunami relief right now:"},{"time":991000,"text":"it's a mechanism for rehydrating"},{"time":993000,"text":"cholera victims that's so simple to use it,"},{"time":996000,"text":"illiterates can be trained to use it."},{"time":999000,"text":"BitTorrent turns every downloader into an uploader,"},{"time":1003000,"text":"making the system more efficient the more it is used."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1008000,"text":"Millions of people have contributed their desktop computers"},{"time":1011000,"text":"when they're not using them to link together through the Internet"},{"time":1016000,"text":"into supercomputing collectives"},{"time":1018000,"text":"that help solve the protein folding problem for medical researchers --"},{"time":1022000,"text":"that's Folding@home at Stanford --"},{"time":1025000,"text":"to crack codes, to search for life in outer space."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1030000,"text":"I don't think we know enough yet."},{"time":1032000,"text":"I don't think we've even begun to discover what the basic principles are,"},{"time":1036000,"text":"but I think we can begin to think about them."},{"time":1039000,"text":"And I don't have enough time to talk about all of them,"},{"time":1042000,"text":"but think about self-interest."},{"time":1044000,"text":"This is all about self-interest that adds up to more."},{"time":1047000,"text":"In El Salvador, both sides that withdrew from their civil war"},{"time":1052000,"text":"took moves that had been proven to mirror a prisoner's dilemma strategy."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1056000,"text":"In the U.S., in the Philippines, in Kenya, around the world,"},{"time":1062000,"text":"citizens have self-organized political protests and"},{"time":1065000,"text":"get out the vote campaigns using mobile devices and SMS."},{"time":1071000,"text":"Is an Apollo Project of cooperation possible?"},{"time":1074000,"text":"A transdisciplinary study of cooperation?"},{"time":1078000,"text":"I believe that the payoff would be very big."},{"time":1082000,"text":"I think we need to begin developing maps of this territory"},{"time":1086000,"text":"so that we can talk about it across disciplines."},{"time":1088000,"text":"And I am not saying that understanding cooperation \n"},{"time":1092000,"text":"is going to cause us to be better people --"},{"time":1096000,"text":"and sometimes people cooperate to do bad things --"},{"time":1099000,"text":"but I will remind you that a few hundred years ago,"},{"time":1102000,"text":"people saw their loved ones die from diseases they thought"},{"time":1106000,"text":"were caused by sin or foreigners or evil spirits."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1111000,"text":"Descartes said we need an entire new way of thinking."},{"time":1115000,"text":"When the scientific method provided that new way of thinking"},{"time":1118000,"text":"and biology showed that microorganisms caused disease,"},{"time":1122000,"text":"suffering was alleviated."},{"time":1125000,"text":"What forms of suffering could be alleviated,"},{"time":1128000,"text":"what forms of wealth could be created"},{"time":1130000,"text":"if we knew a little bit more about cooperation?"},{"time":1133000,"text":"I don't think that this transdisciplinary discourse"},{"time":1137000,"text":"is automatically going to happen;"},{"time":1139000,"text":"it's going to require effort."},{"time":1142000,"text":"So I enlist you to help me get the cooperation project started."},{"time":1148000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":1150000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}